observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed that the:
Municipal Accountant exert best effort to gather documents relative to the fund transfers and identify the dormant unutilized balances;
Municipal Accountant prepare the corresponding aging of Due to NGAs and LGUs accounts and present the same in the Notes to Financial Statements;
Municipal Treasurer refund the unused balances with identified source agencies, or seek their written approval that the balance may be utilized for other certain purposes; and
Concerned Municipal officials effect the implementation of projects under the trust fund for the purpose they were established.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:

Current Cashier to maintain cashbooks and the acting Municipal Treasurer (MT) to record all pertinent transactions, foot and ruled, and certify monthly the cashbooks pertinent to their accountabilities;

Accountable Officers to classify as either cash or check the recording of collections and deposits;

Acting Municipal Treasurer to take charge of the deposit of all collections to the authorized government depository bank, likewise, ensure that the Municipal Treasurer’s Office retains the original copy of validated deposit slips;

Municipal Accountant and the acting MT to have a quarterly reconciliation of  records;

Accountable Officer(s) to render a final report of accountability upon ceasing to act in his official capacity as such; and

Acting Municipal Treasurer to employ adequate safeguards over the accountability of the Special Disbursing Officer and the Office of the Municipal Treasurer.

We recommended the following:

Strengthening the collection of fines and penalties to the households and institutions who violates the said act;

Recycling of junk materials and scraps that could be a source of livelihood;

Promoting organic fertilizers and sale from the vermi-compost to the farmers and   other institutions; and

Enactment of an ordinance that includes residential areas in the collection of garbage fees.

Recommendations
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to reevaluate the existing inventory team under the General Services Office and if warranted, issue an Executive Order to re-create an Inventory Committee and/or reinforce the team’s manpower to:
Conduct the annual physical count of all PPEs in order to update the RPCPPE, otherwise, conduct inventory per account, targeting the most visible ones like buildings and structures  heavy equipment and motor vehicles, starting from the current year acquisitions and backward, a manner to ease the inventory taking due to manpower and time constraints;
Prepare promptly the Report on the Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) and submit to the Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of each year;
Maintain the prescribed stock cards/property cards and (SLC)/(PPELC), and reconcile them with the RPCPPE, as well as, with the accounting ledger cards, to establish the correct amount of the PPE in the financial statements.
The aforementioned audit observation was communicated to Management thru Audit Observation Memorandum No. 2022-01 dated May 30, 2022.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor re-evaluate the formerly assigned Office of the GSO for the said inventory tasks and if warranted, issue an Executive Order to create an Inventory Committee and/or reinforce the said Office’s manpower to:
Conduct the annual physical count of all PPEs in order to update the RPCPPE, otherwise, conduct inventory per account, targeting the most visible ones like buildings and structures, heavy equipment and motor vehicles, starting from the current year acquisitions to prior years, a manner to ease the inventory taking due to manpower and time constraints;

Prepare promptly the Report on the Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) and submit to the Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of each year;

Maintain the prescribed stock cards/property cards and (SLC)/(PPELC), and reconcile them with the RPCPPE, as well as with the accounting ledger cards, to establish the correct amount of the PPE in the financial statements.

We further recommended that the Municipal Mayor assign competent personnel to facilitate setting up of clear policies in the operation, supervision and monitoring of the Inventory Committee just to ensure compliance with the foregoing guidelines and proper safekeeping, recording and reporting of the said properties.

